<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<theorem xmlns="Theorem"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         type="Lemma"
         id="Thm_InfSupProps"
         xsi:schemaLocation="Theorem &#xA;                    file:/C:/xampp/htdocs/moodle2.5/mod/msm/XSLTdocuments/Theorem.xsd">
   <caption>Properties of supremum and infimum</caption>
   <associate type="Explanation">
      <info>
         <info.caption>Explanation</info.caption>
         <para>
            <para.body>For <math>
                  <latex>c\in \RNr</latex>
               </math> and <math>
                  <latex>A\subseteq \RNr</latex>
               </math>,</para.body>
         </para>
         <math.display>
            <latex>cA\ :=\ \Set{ ca\in \RNr \st a\in A}</latex>
         </math.display>
      </info>
   </associate>
   <statement.theorem>
      <para>
         <para.body>For <math>
               <latex>A,B\subseteq\RNr</latex>
            </math> the following hold</para.body>
      </para>
      <part.theorem partid="SupNegativeA">
         <part.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>
                  <math>
                     <latex>\sup(-A) = -\inf(A)</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>\inf(-A) = -\sup(A)</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
         </part.body>
      </part.theorem>
      <part.theorem partid="SupScalarA">
         <part.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>If <math>
                     <latex>c\in \RNr</latex>
                  </math> satisfies <math>
                     <latex> c&gt;0 </latex>
                  </math>, then <math>
                     <latex>\sup(cA) = c\cdot\sup(A)</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>\inf(cA) = c\cdot \inf(A)</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
         </part.body>
      </part.theorem>
      <part.theorem partid="SupASubSetB">
         <part.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>If <math>
                     <latex>A\subseteq B</latex>
                  </math> then <math>
                     <latex>\sup(A) \leq \sup(B)</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>\inf(A)\geq \inf(B)</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
         </part.body>
      </part.theorem>
   </statement.theorem>
   <proof>
      <proof.block>
         <logic>
            <part.ref>SupNegativeA</part.ref>
         </logic>
         <caption>   <math>
               <latex>\sup(-A) = \inf(A)</latex>
            </math>
         </caption>
         <para>
            <para.body>Let <math>
                  <latex>i\in \bar{\RNr}</latex>
               </math> denote the infimum of <math>
                  <latex>A</latex>
               </math>. Then we know</para.body>
         </para>
         <ol>
            <li>
               <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>i\leq A</latex>
                     </math>, and</para.body>
               </para>
            </li>
            <li>
               <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>u\leq i</latex>
                     </math> for all <math>
                        <latex>u\in \bar{\RNr}</latex>
                     </math> with <math>
                        <latex>u\leq A</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
            </li>
         </ol>
         <para>
            <para.body>Using
			<subordinate>
                  <hot>properties</hot>
                  <crossref>
                     <theorem.ref theoremID="Thm_ROrderingProperties"/>
                     <info>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>Look up this theorem</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </info>
                  </crossref>
               </subordinate>
			of multiplying an inequality by a constant, this implies</para.body>
         </para>
         <ol>
            <li>
               <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>-i\geq -A</latex>
                     </math>, and</para.body>
               </para>
            </li>
            <li>
               <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>-u\geq -i</latex>
                     </math> for all <math>
                        <latex>u\in \bar{\RNr}</latex>
                     </math> with <math>
                        <latex>u\leq A</latex>
                     </math>;
				i.e <math>
                        <latex>v\geq -i</latex>
                     </math> for <math>
                        <latex>v\in \bar{\RNr}</latex>
                     </math> with <math>
                        <latex>v\geq -A</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
            </li>
         </ol>
         <para>
            <para.body>This means exactly that <math>
                  <latex>-i=\sup(-A)</latex>
               </math>. – The identity <math>
                  <latex>\inf(-A) = -\sup(A)</latex>
               </math> can be proven by adapting the argument we just gave. Alternatively, we can use the fact we just proved like so:</para.body>
         </para>
         <math.array column="3">
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>\inf(-A)</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>-\sup(-(-A))</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle"/>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=	</latex>
                  </math>
                  <companion>
                     <info>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>Here we use that <math>
                                 <latex>-(-A) = A</latex>
                              </math>.</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </info>
                  </companion>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>-\sup(A)</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
         </math.array>
         <logic>
            <part.ref>SupScalarA</part.ref>
         </logic>
         <caption>   If <math>
               <latex>c\in \RNr</latex>
            </math> satisfies <math>
               <latex> c&gt;0 </latex>
            </math>, then <math>
               <latex>\sup(cA) = c\cdot\sup(A)</latex>
            </math>
         </caption>
         <para>
            <para.body>
               <subordinate>
                  <hot>Let</hot>
                  <info>
                     <info.caption>Try to prove this one yourself!</info.caption>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>If you understand the argument just given you should have no difficulty proving this part.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </subordinate>
               <math>
                  <latex>s\in \bar{\RNr}</latex>
               </math> denote the supremum of <math>
                  <latex>A</latex>
               </math>. Then we know</para.body>
         </para>
         <ol>
            <li>
               <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>A\leq s</latex>
                     </math>, and</para.body>
               </para>
            </li>
            <li>
               <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>s\leq u</latex>
                     </math> for all <math>
                        <latex>u\in \bar{\RNr}</latex>
                     </math> with <math>
                        <latex>A\leq u</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
            </li>
         </ol>
         <para>
            <para.body>This implies</para.body>
         </para>
         <ol>
            <li>
               <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>cA\leq cs</latex>
                     </math>, and</para.body>
               </para>
            </li>
            <li>
               <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>cs\leq v</latex>
                     </math> for all <math>
                        <latex>v\in \bar{\RNr}</latex>
                     </math> with <math>
                        <latex>cA\leq v</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
            </li>
         </ol>
         <para>
            <para.body>Therefore <math>
                  <latex>\sup(cA) = cs = c\sup(A)</latex>
               </math>, as claimed. – The identity <math>
                  <latex>\inf(cA) = c\cdot \inf(A)</latex>
               </math> follows with a similar argument.</para.body>
         </para>
         <logic>
            <part.ref>SupASubSetB</part.ref>
         </logic>
         <caption>   If <math>
               <latex>A\subseteq B</latex>
            </math> then <math>
               <latex>\sup(A) \leq \sup(B)</latex>
            </math>
         </caption>
         <para>
            <para.body>This is so because each upper bound of <math>
                  <latex>B</latex>
               </math> is also an upper bound of <math>
                  <latex>A</latex>
               </math>. Therefore,</para.body>
         </para>
         <math.display>
            <latex>\sup(A) = \text{(least upper bound of $A$)}\ \leq\ \text{(least upper bound of $B$)}</latex>
         </math.display>
         <para>
            <para.body>The inequality <math>
                  <latex>\inf(A) \geq \inf(B)</latex>
               </math> is proved similarly.</para.body>
         </para>
      </proof.block>
   </proof>
</theorem>
